“Hot dog” is a somewhat dated slang term for someone who is a show-off or attention-seeker. It was often used to describe daredevils who performed tricky stunts. “On a roll” is another slang term meaning someone is enjoying continued success. It’s not really necessary in the clue since “hot dog” conveys the meaning all by itself, but I guess it was added for misdirection.

Some bars host “open mic” nights where amateur performers can get up on stage and play to the crowd. Usually, these are comedians, and it’s a way for many aspiring comics to hone their craft and learn what works with an actual audience. It’s “open” mic because it’s open to anyone who wants to sign up for a chance to get on stage. Coffee houses might have open mic nights for poets, but I don’t think this is nearly as common. At least, not since the 1950s when beatniks performing poetry to fellow hippies was a thing.

